{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2d7bd3dd-cdea-41ff-a6b1-37b4d94fbc46","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic. Here's the general guidance based on .NET and macOS diagnostics:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** A `core.<pid>` file should appear in `/cores/`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, ensure SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking core dumps. On newer macOS, you may need to:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **For .NET-specific analysis**, load the SOS debugging extension in lldb:\n   ```\n   (lldb) plugin load /path/to/libsosplugin.dylib\n   ```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` since there's no CoreCLR runtime. macOS native core dumps via `ulimit -c unlimited` are the standard fallback. Ensure your app is built with debug symbols (`-p:StripSymbols=false`) for meaningful stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17f5cd6f-fee7-4db7-8e85-4563843f04fb","outputTokens":351,"requestId":"F881:203D52:52B30AC:5B09D69:69FA0041"},"id":"3edec455-cfe0-45e1-903b-06446fbd9d55","timestamp":"2026-05-05T14:35:56.755Z","parentId":"ba998212-9b2a-46be-8f57-cac3d679e7a3"}
